            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Miller\u2019s life is steeped in the ink and ghosts of a San Francisco that\u2019s rapidly fading. Raised in the quiet, sun-drenched suburbs of Walnut Creek by a teacher and an engineer, David saw San Francisco as a magnetic beacon of culture and chaos. He attended UC Berkeley, drawn to its legacy of activism and intellectual fervor, and graduated with a journalism degree in the early 90s, full of romantic notions about breaking stories and speaking truth to power.\n\nHis first job was a dream realized: a staff writer for the *SF Bay Guardian*. He thrived on the energy of the newsroom, the smell of newsprint, and the feeling of covering the city\u2019s vibrant, gritty underbelly. Those were his golden years, spent in smoky dive bars with fellow reporters, arguing politics and chasing leads. He met his now ex-wife, a graphic designer, during this period; their shared passion for the city\u2019s creative scene was the bedrock of their decade-long marriage, which ultimately buckled under the weight of divergent career paths.\n\nThe key turning point was the dot-com bust and the subsequent implosion of print media. It was a slow, painful death. David watched as his beloved paper folded, forcing a wrenching transition into the world of digital media. He felt like a sellout, trading journalistic integrity for SEO keywords and click-through rates. Now a Senior Arts & Culture Editor for a large online information portal, he sees himself as a guardian at the gate, fighting a quiet, daily battle to champion genuine art and thoughtful criticism against an endless tide of listicles and algorithm-driven content.\n\nToday, David lives alone in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset, a sanctuary filled with books, vinyl records, and posters from long-closed music venues. His day begins with the familiar rumble of the N-Judah, which he rides to his sterile SoMa office. He maintains a small, tight circle of friends\u2014fellow veterans of the print era\u2014with whom he shares nostalgic dinners. His connection to San Francisco is one of a loving, concerned custodian. He dreams of one day writing a book, a personal history of the city\u2019s lost artists and spaces, to ensure the soul of the San Francisco he fell in love with is never truly forgotten."
